#: ../../../containers.rst:59
msgid "Exporting Spack installations as Container Images"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:61
msgid "The command"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:63
msgid ""
"spack buildcache push [--base-image BASE_IMAGE] [--tag TAG] mirror [specs...]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:67
msgid ""
"creates and pushes a container image to an OCI-compatible container "
"registry, with the ``mirror`` argument specifying a registry (see below)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:69
msgid ""
"Think of this command less as \"building a container\" and more as archiving "
"a working software stack into a portable image."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:71
msgid ""
"Container images created this way are **minimal**: they contain only runtime "
"dependencies of the specified specs, the base image, and nothing else. Spack "
"itself is *not* included in the resulting image."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:74
msgid "The arguments are as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:76
msgid "``--base-image BASE_IMAGE``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:77
msgid ""
"Specifies the base image to use for the container. This should be a minimal "
"Linux distribution with a libc that is compatible with the host system. For "
"example, if your host system is Ubuntu 22.04, you can use ``ubuntu:22.04``, "
"``ubuntu:24.04``, or newer: the libc in the container image must be at least "
"the version of the host system, assuming ABI compatibility. It is also "
"perfectly fine to use a completely different Linux distribution as long as "
"the libc is compatible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:82
msgid "``--tag TAG``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:83
msgid ""
"Specifies a container image tag to use. This tag is used for the image "
"consisting of all specs specified in the command line together."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:86
msgid "``mirror`` argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:87
msgid ""
"Either the name of a configured OCI registry image (in ``mirrors.yaml``), or "
"a URL specifying the registry and image name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:89
msgid ""
"When pushing to remote registries, you will typically :ref:`specify the name "
"of a registry <configuring-container-registries>` from your Spack "
"configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:90
msgid ""
"When pushing to a local registry, you can simply specify a URL like "
"``oci+http://localhost:5000/[image]``, where ``[image]`` is the name of the "
"image to create, and ``oci+http://`` indicates that the registry does not "
"support HTTPS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:92
msgid "``specs...`` arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:93
msgid ""
"is a list of Spack specs to include in the image. These are packages that "
"have already been installed by Spack. When a Spack environment is activated, "
"only the packages in the environment are included in the image. If no specs "
"are given, and a Spack environment is active, all packages in the "
"environment are included."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:98
msgid ""
"Spack publishes every individual dependency as a separate image layer, which "
"allows for efficient storage and transfer of images with overlapping "
"dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:101
msgid ""
"The Docker ``overlayfs2`` storage driver is limited to 128 layers, above "
"which a ``max depth exceeded`` error may be produced when pulling the image. "
"You can hit this limit when exporting container images from larger "
"environments or packages with many dependencies. There are `alternative "
"drivers <https://docs.docker.com/storage/storagedriver/>`_ to work around "
"this limitation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:105
msgid ""
"The ``spack buildcache push --base-image ...`` command serves a **dual "
"purpose**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:107
msgid ""
"It makes container images available for container runtimes like Docker and "
"Podman."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:108
msgid ""
"It makes the *same* binaries available :ref:`as a build cache "
"<binary_caches_oci>` for ``spack install``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:113
msgid "Container registries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:115
msgid ""
"The ``spack buildcache push`` command exports container images directly to "
"an OCI-compatible container registry, such as Docker Hub, GitHub Container "
"Registry (GHCR), Amazon ECR, Google GCR, Azure ACR, or a private registry."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:117
msgid ""
"These services require authentication, which is configured with the ``spack "
"mirror add`` command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:119
msgid ""
"$ spack mirror add \\\n"
"      --oci-username-variable REGISTRY_USER \\\n"
"      --oci-password-variable REGISTRY_TOKEN \\\n"
"      example-registry \\\n"
"      oci://example.com/name/image"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:127
msgid ""
"This registers a mirror named ``example-registry`` in your ``mirrors.yaml`` "
"configuration file that is associated with a container registry and image "
"``example.com/name/image``. The registry can then be referred to by its "
"name, e.g. ``spack buildcache push example-registry ...``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:130
msgid ""
"The ``oci://`` scheme in the URL indicates that this is an OCI-compatible "
"registry with HTTPS support. If you only specify ``oci://name/image``, Spack "
"will assume the registry is hosted on Docker Hub."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:133
msgid ""
"The ``--oci-username-variable`` and ``--oci-password-variable`` options "
"specify the names of *environment variables* that will be used to "
"authenticate with the registry. Spack does not store your credentials in "
"configuration files; it expects you to set the corresponding environment "
"variables in your shell before running the ``spack buildcache push`` command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:136
msgid "$ REGISTRY_USER=user REGISTRY_TOKEN=token spack buildcache push ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:142
msgid ""
"The registry password is typically a *personal access token* (PAT) generated "
"on the registry website or a command line tool. In the section :ref:`oci-"
"authentication` we list specific examples for popular registries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:145
msgid ""
"If you don't have access to a remote registry, or wish to experiment with "
"container images locally, you can run a *local registry* on your machine and "
"let Spack push to it. This is as simple as running the `official registry "
"image <https://hub.docker.com/_/registry>`_ in the background:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:148
msgid "$ docker run -d -p 5000:5000 --name registry registry"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:152
msgid ""
"In this case, it is not necessary to configure a named mirror, you can "
"simply refer to it by URL using ``oci+http://localhost:5000/[image]``, where "
"``[image]`` is the name of the image to create, and ``oci+http://`` "
"indicates that the registry does not support HTTPS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:157
msgid "Example 1: pushing selected specs as container images"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:159
msgid ""
"Assume we have ``python@3.13`` and ``cmake@3`` already installed by Spack, "
"and we want to push them as a combined container image ``software_stack:"
"latest`` to a local registry."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:161
msgid "First we verify that the specs are indeed installed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:163
msgid ""
"$ spack find --long python@3.13 cmake@3\n"
"\n"
"-- linux-ubuntu24.04-zen2 / %c,cxx=gcc@13.3.0 -------------------\n"
"scpgv2h cmake@3.31.8  n54tvjw python@3.13.5"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:170
msgid ""
"Since these are the only installations on our system, we can simply refer to "
"them by their spec strings. In case there are multiple installations, we "
"could use ``python/n54tvjw`` and ``cmake/scpgv2h`` to uniquely refer to them "
"by hashes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:173
msgid ""
"We now use ``spack buildcache push`` to publish these packages as a "
"container image with ``ubuntu:24.04`` as a base image:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:175
msgid ""
"$ spack buildcache push \\\n"
"      --base-image ubuntu:24.04 \\\n"
"      --tag latest \\\n"
"      oci+http://localhost:5000/software_stack \\\n"
"      python@3.13 cmake@3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:183
msgid ""
"They can now be pulled and run with Docker or any other OCI-compatible "
"container runtime:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:185
msgid ""
"$ docker run -it localhost:5000/software_stack:latest\n"
"root@container-id:/# python3 --version\n"
"Python 3.13.5\n"
"root@container-id:/# cmake --version\n"
"cmake version 3.31.8"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:196
msgid "Example 2: pushing entire Spack environments as container images"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:198
msgid ""
"In this example we show how to export an installed :ref:`Spack environment "
"<environments>` as a container image and push it to a remote registry."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:200
msgid ""
"# Create and install an environment\n"
"$ spack env create .\n"
"$ spack -e . add python@3.13 cmake@3\n"
"$ spack -e . install\n"
"\n"
"# Configure a remote registry\n"
"$ spack -e . mirror add \\\n"
"      --oci-username-variable REGISTRY_USER \\\n"
"      --oci-password-variable REGISTRY_TOKEN \\\n"
"      container-registry \\\n"
"      oci://example.com/name/image\n"
"\n"
"# Push the image\n"
"$ REGISTRY_USER=user REGISTRY_TOKEN=token \\\n"
"  spack -e . buildcache push \\\n"
"      --update-index \\\n"
"      --base-image ubuntu:24.04 \\\n"
"      --tag my_env \\\n"
"      container-registry"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:222
msgid "The resulting container image can then be run as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:224
msgid ""
"$ docker run -it example.com/name/image:my_env\n"
"root@container-id:/# python3 --version\n"
"Python 3.13.5\n"
"root@container-id:/# cmake --version\n"
"cmake version 3.31.8"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:232
msgid ""
"The advantage of using a Spack environment is that we do not have to specify "
"the individual specs on the command line when pushing the image. With "
"environments, all root specs and their runtime dependencies are included in "
"the container image."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:235
msgid ""
"If you do specify specs in ``spack buildcache push`` with an environment "
"active, only those matching specs from the environment are included in the "
"image."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:241
msgid "Generating recipes for Docker and Singularity"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:243
msgid ""
"Apart from exporting existing installations into container images, Spack can "
"also generate recipes for container images. This is useful if you want to "
"run Spack itself in a sandboxed environment instead of on the host system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:246
msgid ""
"This approach requires you to have a container runtime like Docker or "
"Singularity installed on your system, and can only be used using Spack "
"environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:248
msgid "Since recipes need a little more boilerplate than:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:250
msgid ""
"COPY spack.yaml /environment\n"
"RUN spack -e /environment install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:255
msgid ""
"Spack provides a command to generate customizable recipes for container "
"images. Customizations include minimizing the size of the image, installing "
"packages in the base image using the system package manager, and setting up "
"a proper entrypoint to run the image."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:261
msgid "A Quick Introduction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:263
msgid "Consider having a Spack environment like the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:265
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - gromacs+mpi\n"
"  - mpich"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:272
msgid ""
"Producing a ``Dockerfile`` from it is as simple as changing directories to "
"where the ``spack.yaml`` file is stored and running the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:274
msgid "$ spack containerize > Dockerfile"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:278
msgid ""
"The ``Dockerfile`` that gets created uses multi-stage builds and other "
"techniques to minimize the size of the final image:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:280
msgid ""
"# Build stage with Spack pre-installed and ready to be used\n"
"FROM spack/ubuntu-jammy:develop AS builder\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"# What we want to install and how we want to install it\n"
"# is specified in a manifest file (spack.yaml)\n"
"RUN mkdir -p /opt/spack-environment && \\\n"
"set -o noclobber \\\n"
"&&  (echo spack: \\\n"
"&&   echo '  specs:' \\\n"
"&&   echo '  - gromacs+mpi' \\\n"
"&&   echo '  - mpich' \\\n"
"&&   echo '  concretizer:' \\\n"
"&&   echo '    unify: true' \\\n"
"&&   echo '  config:' \\\n"
"&&   echo '    install_tree:' \\\n"
"&&   echo '      root: /opt/software' \\\n"
"&&   echo '  view: /opt/views/view') > /opt/spack-environment/spack.yaml\n"
"\n"
"# Install the software, remove unnecessary deps\n"
"RUN cd /opt/spack-environment && spack env activate . && spack install --"
"fail-fast && spack gc -y\n"
"\n"
"# Strip all the binaries\n"
"RUN find -L /opt/views/view/* -type f -exec readlink -f '{}' \\; | \\\n"
"    xargs file -i | \\\n"
"    grep 'charset=binary' | \\\n"
"    grep 'x-executable\\|x-archive\\|x-sharedlib' | \\\n"
"    awk -F: '{print $1}' | xargs strip\n"
"\n"
"# Modifications to the environment that are necessary to run\n"
"RUN cd /opt/spack-environment && \\\n"
"    spack env activate --sh -d . > activate.sh\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"# Bare OS image to run the installed executables\n"
"FROM ubuntu:22.04\n"
"\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/spack-environment /opt/spack-environment\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/software /opt/software\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/views /opt/views\n"
"\n"
"RUN { \\\n"
"      echo '#!/bin/sh' \\\n"
"      && echo '.' /opt/spack-environment/activate.sh \\\n"
"      && echo 'exec \"$@\"'; \\\n"
"    } > /entrypoint.sh \\\n"
"&& chmod a+x /entrypoint.sh \\\n"
"&& ln -s /opt/views/view /opt/view\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"ENTRYPOINT [ \"/entrypoint.sh\" ]\n"
"CMD [ \"/bin/bash\" ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:336
msgid ""
"The image itself can then be built and run in the usual way with any of the "
"tools suitable for the task. For instance, if we decided to use Docker:"
